posts.name: Ryan zheng
posts.cooked: Hello, I am trying to set a static ip address using this tutorial, Networking - PhotonVision Docs , but for some reason after I follow all the instructions, the ip address doesn’t change to 10.TE.AM.11:5800 but instead is set at 10.TE.AM.57:5800 (where TE.AM is my team number of course) Is there any way I can force the ip address to be set at 10.TE.Am.11:5800? I don’t know what to do. Thanks!

posts.name: Alex
posts.cooked: What hardware is this running on?

posts.name: Ryan zheng
posts.cooked: I’m running photon vision on a beelink coprocessor running ubuntu

posts.name: Alex
posts.cooked: From my experience I have only got PhotonVision’s static ip setter to work on official images. If you have enough linux skill you could go manually change it but I would just use the hostname.

posts.name: Ryan zheng
posts.cooked: Wait, I’m a bit new to all of this so could you clarify how I use the hostname to access photonvision?

posts.name: Ryan zheng
posts.cooked: I tried accessing photonvision.local:5800 but it doesn’t connect. I made sure the hostname was correct as well. Any suggestions? Thanks!

posts.name: Technologyman00
posts.cooked:

ubuntu
